In order to separate infants from the other abalone, We store the infant abalone in dataset iab

 iab <- aba %>% filter(Sex =="I") 
 iab

The rest of the adult abalone in dataset fmab

fmab <-aba %>% filter(Sex !="I")
fmab

We test for the difference in length, diameter, height of an infant ablone and adult abalone with Welch two sample t- tests

t.test(iab$Length,fmab$Length)

    Welch Two Sample t-test

The p value of less than 2.2 x 10^-16 in the three tests above shows that the length, diameter, height of infant abalone is not similar to adult abalone. These features can therefore be used to distinguish between infants and adults.

A 95% confidence interval is used to correctly identify an infant abalone from it Length Diameter and Height.

Table 1. Range of Length , Diameter and Height of Infant abalone at 95% confidence

From the above table any abalone which has a Length up to 87mm, Diameter up to 67mm and Height up to 22mm can be considered as infants and therefore should be avoided from harvesting.

For abalone beyond these dimensions we use a classification model which classifies an abalone based on its length, diameter and height.

For this purpose we compare a Support Vector Machine model (SVM) , Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)

Testing for Multivariate Normality of Length, Diameter and Height

(mvn(aba[,c(2,3,4)]))$univariateNormality

As the three independent variables are not univairate or multivariate normal, by default, SVM could the preferable classifier model

Support Vector Machine (SVM)

set.seed(111)
ind <- sample(2, nrow(aba), 
              replace = TRUE, 
              prob = c(.8, .2))
training <- aba[ind==1,]
testing <- aba[ind==2,]
(tuasvm <- tune.svm(Sex ~ Length+ Diameter + Height,data=training,kernel="radial", gamma = 10^(-1:1), cost = 10^(-1:1)))

Correlation Analysis

ggpairs(aba[,c(2,3,4,6,7)])

The two variables do not have univariate or multivariate normality

Correlation between the independent variables Length, Diameter and Height

cor(aba[,c(2,3,4)])
            Length  Diameter    Height
Length   1.0000000 0.9868116 0.8275536
Diameter 0.9868116 1.0000000 0.8336837
Height   0.8275536 0.8336837 1.0000000

This shows shows that all the three independent variables are highly correlated indicating high multicollinearity. A correlation between length and diameter of 0.986 makes it possible for us to ignore one of them in our modelling. We will test for its effect on our modelling. We will however for now use all three Length, Diameter and Height.

Correlation between the dependent variables Viscera Weight, Shucked Weight and Shell Weight

cor(aba[,c(6,7,8)])

The three hypothesis tests broadly agree and as the p value for both canonical correlations is less than 0.05 we can consider that both canonical correlations are statically significant.

However, as seen above are variables are not multivariate normal and the population size is small so these test may generate some errors

Multivariate Linear Modeling and Analysis

We would build a linear model to predict shucked weight and visceral weight by regressing over independent variables of Length, Diameter and Height.

amlm <- lm(cbind(`Shucked weight`,`Viscera weight`)~Length+Diameter+Height, data=aba)

As we have seen above the correlation between Length and Diameter is 0.98 making them highly correlated. We therefore test if diameter has an extra predictive effect on the shucked and viscera weights.

ramlm<- lm(cbind(`Shucked weight`,`Viscera weight`)~Length+Height, data=aba)
anova(amlm,ramlm)
Analysis of Variance Table

Model 1: cbind(`Shucked weight`, `Viscera weight`) ~ Length + Diameter + 
    Height
Model 2: cbind(`Shucked weight`, `Viscera weight`) ~ Length + Height
  Res.Df Df Gen.var.    Pillai approx F num Df den Df    Pr(>F)    
1   4173      137.63                                               
2   4174  1   138.18 0.0084887   17.859      2   4172 1.892e-08 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

This test gives a p value less than 0.05 and therefore conclude that Diameter has an effect on the prediction of shucked and viscera weight

predict(amlm, newdata = testing[1:5,] ,interval ='confidence')
  Shucked weight Viscera weight
1       42.59520      21.105876
2      101.81039      50.955214

Pearson Residuals

sds <- amlm %>% estVar %>% diag %>% sqrt
PR <- sweep(resid(amlm), 2, sds,)
ggpairs(as_tibble(PR))

res<- resid(amlm)
plot(fitted(amlm), res)
abline(0,0)

The above two graphs of residues show that this linear model is good fit for the given data.

We can therefore conclude that we have a linear model for each, shucked and viscera weight

Viscera Weight = -48.339 + 0.502 Length + 0.255 Diameter + 0.391 Height

Shucked Weight = -99.107 + 1.352 Length + 0.474 Diameter + 0.476 Height
